For this assignment, I chose to focus on census tracts within the 12 CA counties which comprise the San Joaquin Valley region, as determined by the States new COVID-19 closure thresholds. Map of San Joaquin Valley region, as determined by State

I was interested in comparing the percentage of population in each census tract that have a bachelors degree or higher vs.the percent with some form of medical insurance. To get at this data, I used items contained in B27019, health insurance coverage status and type by age and educational attainment. The data is broken into two general age brackets - folks aged 25 to 64 and those 65+ (presumably because once folks hit the age of 65, they become eligible for MediCare). I isolated the percentage of folks between 25 - 64 with bachelors degrees/higher in each census tract (roughly normally distributed, ranging from 0 to approx. 55%) and compared them against the broad percent with insurance (roughly normally distributed, ranging from about 40% to 100%, with the majority of census tracts between 60% and 80% insured.)

### brainstorm: educational attainment vs health insurance status
Sys.setenv(CENSUS_KEY="8a30b488e19d78df02c748f4833ec25ed94fffa6")

acs_vars_2018_5yr <-
  listCensusMetadata(
    name = "2018/acs/acs5",
    type = "variables"
  )


sj_insurance_edu_tract <- 
  getCensus(
    name = "acs/acs5",
    vintage = 2018,
    region = "tract:*",
    regionin = "state:06+county:009,019,029,031,039,043,047,069,077,099,107,109",
    vars = c(
      "B27019_018E",
      "B27019_001E",
      "B27019_019E",
      "B27019_009E",
      "B27019_004E",
      "B27019_014E"
    )
  ) %>% 
  transmute(
    tract = paste0(state, county, tract),
    perc_bachelorsdegreehigher = B27019_018E / B27019_001E,
    perc_withinsurance = (B27019_019E + B27019_009E + B27019_004E + B27019_014E) / B27019_001E
  ) %>% 
  filter(
    !is.na(perc_bachelorsdegreehigher), 
    !is.na(perc_withinsurance)
  )


ggplot(
    data = sj_insurance_edu_tract,
    aes(
      x = perc_bachelorsdegreehigher,
      y = perc_withinsurance
    )
  ) +
  geom_point() +
  geom_smooth(method = "lm")
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

model <- lm(perc_withinsurance ~ perc_bachelorsdegreehigher, sj_insurance_edu_tract)

summary(model)

The regression analysis indicates that there is indeed a statistically significant relationship (at a less than .001 p-value) between an increasing percentage of residents that have a bachelors degree or higher and an increasing percentage with health insurance in these census tracts. Holding all other things equal, it appears that having a bachelors degree is associated with an additional 23.7% likelihood of possessing health insurance. There is wide variability - bachelors degree possession only describes 10% of the variance in insurance (from the r-squared), but it is a significant contributing. factor.

For this part of the assignment, I aimed to further investigate the contributing factors and barriers to residents of the Central Valley in accessing health insurance. We established (above) that there is a relationship between educational attainment and health insurance status. We also know from a wide range of studies and news accounts that immigrants - and particularly those without citizenship status - encounter major barriers in accessing healthcare. This has become even more pronounced equity consideration during the COVID-19 pandemic - without access to trusted and easily-accessed COVID testing and treatment, residents risk further endangering their own health, their families or other household members, and entire community.

Literature referenced - Health Coverage of Undocumented Immigrants - Kaiser Family Foundation - Health Coverage of Immigrants - Kaiser Family Foundation - Left Out: Immigrants Access to Health Care and Insurance - Medical News Today - US election result: Impact on healthcare for undocumented communities

To hone in on this more, I chose to build a multiple regression analysis of individuals in the San Joaquin Valley comparing a) health insurance status (possessing health insurance or not), b) educational attainment (possessing a bachelors degree and above, or not), and c) citizenship status (possessing US citizenship or not).

ca_pumas <-
  pumas("CA", cb = T, progress_bar = F)

pums_vars_2018_distinct_pp <- 
  pums_vars_2018 %>%
  distinct(var_code, var_label, data_type, level) %>% 
  filter(level == "person")

### isolating to the San Joaquin Valley counties

sj_valley_names <-
  c(
    "Calaveras",
    "Fresno",
    "Kern",
    "Kings",
    "Madera",
    "Mariposa",
    "Merced",
    "San Benito",
    "San Joaquin",
    "Stanislaus",
    "Tulare",
    "Tuolumne"
  )

sj_counties <-
  counties("CA", cb = T, progress_bar = F) %>%
  filter(NAME %in% sj_valley_names)

sj_pumas <-
  ca_pumas %>% 
  st_centroid() %>% 
  .[sj_counties, ] %>% 
  st_set_geometry(NULL) %>% 
  left_join(ca_pumas %>% select(GEOID10)) %>% 
  st_as_sf()
## Warning in st_centroid.sf(.): st_centroid assumes attributes are constant over
## geometries of x
## Warning in st_centroid.sfc(st_geometry(x), of_largest_polygon =
## of_largest_polygon): st_centroid does not give correct centroids for longitude/
## latitude data
## although coordinates are longitude/latitude, st_intersects assumes that they are planar
## although coordinates are longitude/latitude, st_intersects assumes that they are planar
## Joining, by = "GEOID10"
sj_pums <-
  ca_pums %>% 
  filter(PUMA %in% sj_pumas$PUMACE10)

sj_pums_example <-
  sj_pums %>% 
  filter(!duplicated(SERIALNO)) %>%  
  mutate(
    healthinsurance = ifelse(
      (HICOV==1),
      PWGTP,
      0),
    citizen = ifelse(
      (CIT!=5),
      PWGTP,
      0),
    collegegrad = ifelse(
      (SCHL==20)|(SCHL==21)|(SCHL==22)|(SCHL==23)|(SCHL==24),
      PWGTP,
      0
    ) 
  )

After calling all of the PUMS in the San Joaquin Valley and weighting the population sizes, I prepared a multiple regression comparing individuals who have health insurance to citizenship status and if they were a college graduate or not. I turned each of these statuses into binaries (posession of health insurance or not / citizen or not / college grad or not), and performed the multiple regression on the weighted values.

correlationplot <- sj_pums_example %>% 
  select(
    healthinsurance, 
    citizen,
    collegegrad
  ) %>% 
  cor()

corrplot(
  correlationplot, 
  method = "number",
  type = "upper"
)

model <- lm(healthinsurance ~ citizen+collegegrad, sj_pums_example)

summary(model)

The regression plot indicates there is a statistically significant relationship between the combination of health insurance, being a citizen, and being a college graduate. In this analysis, it seems that being a citizen seems to have better predictive power (on having health insurance) compared to educational attainment. This does confirm the literature review above that not being a citizen remains a strongly correlated factor in whether or not a resident has health insurance (perhaps more so than educational attainment).

This does not indicate causation, but could indicate correlation at the 1% significance level (or greater).

I chose to go back to the original simple regression, and ask - does citizenship status help explain a greater amount of variance when considering the relationship between educational attainment and health insurance status? I collected the ACS data from 2018 asking similar questions - the percentage of residents in each census tract that have insurance, the percentage that are citizens, and the percentage that have a bachelors degree or higher.

acs_vars_2018_5yr <-
  listCensusMetadata(
    name = "2018/acs/acs5",
    type = "variables"
  )

sj_multipleregression_tract <- 
  getCensus(
    name = "acs/acs5",
    vintage = 2018,
    region = "tract:*",
    regionin = "state:06+county:009,019,029,031,039,043,047,069,077,099,107,109",
    vars = c(
      "B27019_018E",
      "B27019_001E",
      "B27019_019E",
      "B27019_009E",
      "B27019_004E",
      "B27019_014E",
      "B27020_013E",
      "B27020_001E"
    )
  ) %>% 
  transmute(
    tract = paste0(state, county, tract),
    perc_bachelorsdegreehigher = B27019_018E / B27019_001E,
    perc_withinsurance = (B27019_019E + B27019_009E + B27019_004E + B27019_014E) / B27019_001E,
    perc_citizen = 1-(B27020_013E / B27020_001E)
  ) %>% 
  filter(
    !is.na(perc_bachelorsdegreehigher), 
    !is.na(perc_withinsurance),
    !is.na(perc_citizen)
  )


correlationplot <- sj_multipleregression_tract %>% 
  select(
    perc_withinsurance, 
    perc_citizen,
    perc_bachelorsdegreehigher,
  ) %>% 
  cor()

corrplot(
  correlationplot, 
  method = "number",
  type = "upper"
)

model <- lm(perc_withinsurance ~ perc_citizen+perc_bachelorsdegreehigher, sj_multipleregression_tract)

summary(model)

This multiple regression analysis, based on the ACS daata within census tracts, complicates the picture we took away from the PUMS data above. Here we see a weak relationship between the percentage of citizens in a census tract and the percent of residents with insurance. This indicates a stronger relationship between attaining a bachelors degree or higher and possessing citizenship.

This makes me wonder: - Could the ecological rather than individual focus obscure the number of undocumented residents without insurance? In this model, population size of relative census tracts is not weighted. Undocumented residents without insurance could be densely concentrated in a small number of census tracts, which would affect the strength of the regression. - Could the ACS undercount noncitizens? We know that there has been significant controversy in recent years over the inclusion of more detailed citizenship questions. Could that have suprressed the numbers included re: noncitizens?
